    The time for the Passover Festival was near, and many people went up from the country to Jerusalem to perform the ritual of purification before the festival.\par
    They were looking for Jesus, and as they gathered in the Temple, they asked one another, "What do you think? Surely he will not come to the festival, will he?"\par
    The chief priests and the Pharisees had given orders that if anyone knew where Jesus was, he must report it, so that they could arrest him.\par
    Six days before the Passover, Jesus went to Bethany, the home of Lazarus, the man he had raised from death.\par
    They prepared a dinner for him there, which Martha helped serve; Lazarus was one of those who were sitting at the table with Jesus.\par
    Then Mary took a whole pint of a very expensive perfume made of pure nard, poured it on Jesus' feet, and wiped them with her hair. The sweet smell of the perfume filled the whole house.\par
    One of Jesus' disciples, Judas Iscariot - the one who was going to betray him - said,\par
    "Why wasn't this perfume sold for three hundred silver coins and the money given to the poor?"\par
    He said this, not because he cared about the poor, but because he was a thief. He carried the money bag and would help himself from it.\par
    But Jesus said, "Leave her alone! Let her keep what she has for the day of my burial.\par
    You will always have poor people with you, but you will not always have me."\par
    A large number of people heard that Jesus was in Bethany, so they went there, not only because of Jesus but also to see Lazarus, whom Jesus had raised from death.\par
    So the chief priests made plans to kill Lazarus too,\par
    because on his account many Jews were rejecting them and believing in Jesus.\par
    The next day the large crowd that had come to the Passover Festival heard that Jesus was coming to Jerusalem.\par
    So they took branches of palm trees and went out to meet him, shouting, "Praise God! God bless him who comes in the name of the Lord! God bless the King of Israel!"\par
    Jesus found a donkey and rode on it, just as the scripture says,\par
    "Do not be afraid, city of Zion! Here comes your king, riding on a young donkey."\par
    His disciples did not understand this at the time; but when Jesus had been raised to glory, they remembered that the scripture said this about him and that they had done this for him.\par
    The people who had been with Jesus when he called Lazarus out of the grave and raised him from death had reported what had happened.\par
    That was why the crowd met him - because they heard that he had performed this miracle.\par
    The Pharisees then said to one another, "You see, we are not succeeding at all! Look, the whole world is following him!"\par
    Some Greeks were among those who had gone to Jerusalem to worship during the festival.\par
    They went to Philip (he was from Bethsaida in Galilee) and said, "Sir, we want to see Jesus."\par
    Philip went and told Andrew, and the two of them went and told Jesus.\par
    Jesus answered them, "The hour has now come for the Son of Man to receive great glory.\par
    I am telling you the truth: a grain of wheat remains no more than a single grain unless it is dropped into the ground and dies. If it does die, then it produces many grains.\par
    Those who love their own life will lose it; those who hate their own life in this world will keep it for life eternal.\par
    Whoever wants to serve me must follow me, so that my servant will be with me where I am. And my Father will honor anyone who serves me.\par
    "Now my heart is troubled - and what shall I say? Shall I say, "Father, do not let this hour come upon me'? But that is why I came - so that I might go through this hour of suffering.\par
    Father, bring glory to your name!" Then a voice spoke from heaven, "I have brought glory to it, and I will do so again."\par
    The crowd standing there heard the voice, and some of them said it was thunder, while others said, "An angel spoke to him!"\par
    But Jesus said to them, "It was not for my sake that this voice spoke, but for yours.\par
    Now is the time for this world to be judged; now the ruler of this world will be overthrown.\par
    When I am lifted up from the earth, I will draw everyone to me.\par
    (In saying this he indicated the kind of death he was going to suffer.)\par
    The crowd answered, "Our Law tells us that the Messiah will live forever. How, then, can you say that the Son of Man must be lifted up? Who is this Son of Man?"\par
    Jesus answered, "The light will be among you a little longer. Continue on your way while you have the light, so that the darkness will not come upon you; for the one who walks in the dark does not know where he is going.\par
    Believe in the light, then, while you have it, so that you will be the people of the light." After Jesus said this, he went off and hid himself from them.\par
    Even though he had performed all these miracles in their presence, they did not believe in him,\par
    so that what the prophet Isaiah had said might come true: "Lord, who believed the message we told? To whom did the Lord reveal his power?"\par
    And so they were not able to believe, because Isaiah also said,\par
    "God has blinded their eyes and closed their minds, so that their eyes would not see, and their minds would not understand, and they would not turn to me, says God, for me to heal them."\par
    Isaiah said this because he saw Jesus' glory and spoke about him.\par
    Even then, many Jewish authorities believed in Jesus; but because of the Pharisees they did not talk about it openly, so as not to be expelled from the synagogue.\par
    They loved human approval rather than the approval of God.\par
    Jesus said in a loud voice, "Whoever believes in me believes not only in me but also in him who sent me.\par
    Whoever sees me sees also him who sent me.\par
    I have come into the world as light, so that everyone who believes in me should not remain in the darkness.\par
    If people hear my message and do not obey it, I will not judge them. I came, not to judge the world, but to save it.\par
    Those who reject me and do not accept my message have one who will judge them. The words I have spoken will be their judge on the last day!\par
    This is true, because I have not spoken on my own authority, but the Father who sent me has commanded me what I must say and speak.\par
    And I know that his command brings eternal life. What I say, then, is what the Father has told me to say."\par
    It was now the day before the Passover Festival. Jesus knew that the hour had come for him to leave this world and go to the Father. He had always loved those in the world who were his own, and he loved them to the very end.\par
    Jesus and his disciples were at supper. The Devil had already put into the heart of Judas, the son of Simon Iscariot, the thought of betraying Jesus.\par
    Jesus knew that the Father had given him complete power; he knew that he had come from God and was going to God.\par
    So he rose from the table, took off his outer garment, and tied a towel around his waist.\par
    Then he poured some water into a washbasin and began to wash the disciples' feet and dry them with the towel around his waist.\par
    He came to Simon Peter, who said to him, "Are you going to wash my feet, Lord?"\par
    Jesus answered him, "You do not understand now what I am doing, but you will understand later."\par
    Peter declared, "Never at any time will you wash my feet!" "If I do not wash your feet," Jesus answered, "you will no longer be my disciple."\par
    Simon Peter answered, "Lord, do not wash only my feet, then! Wash my hands and head, too!"\par
    Jesus said, "Those who have taken a bath are completely clean and do not have to wash themselves, except for their feet. All of you are clean - all except one.\par
    (Jesus already knew who was going to betray him; that is why he said, "All of you, except one, are clean.")\par
    After Jesus had washed their feet, he put his outer garment back on and returned to his place at the table. "Do you understand what I have just done to you?" he asked.\par
    "You call me Teacher and Lord, and it is right that you do so, because that is what I am.\par
    I, your Lord and Teacher, have just washed your feet. You, then, should wash one another's feet.\par
    I have set an example for you, so that you will do just what I have done for you.\par
    I am telling you the truth: no slaves are greater than their master, and no messengers are greater than the one who sent them.\par
    Now that you know this truth, how happy you will be if you put it into practice!\par
    "I am not talking about all of you; I know those I have chosen. But the scripture must come true that says, "The man who shared my food turned against me.'\par
    I tell you this now before it happens, so that when it does happen, you will believe that "I Am Who I Am.'\par
    I am telling you the truth: whoever receives anyone I send receives me also; and whoever receives me receives him who sent me."\par
    After Jesus had said this, he was deeply troubled and declared openly, "I am telling you the truth: one of you is going to betray me."\par
    The disciples looked at one another, completely puzzled about whom he meant.\par
    One of the disciples, the one whom Jesus loved, was sitting next to Jesus.\par
    Simon Peter motioned to him and said, "Ask him whom he is talking about."\par
    So that disciple moved closer to Jesus' side and asked, "Who is it, Lord?"\par
    Jesus answered, "I will dip some bread in the sauce and give it to him; he is the man." So he took a piece of bread, dipped it, and gave it to Judas, the son of Simon Iscariot.\par
    As soon as Judas took the bread, Satan entered into him. Jesus said to him, "Hurry and do what you must!"\par
    None of the others at the table understood why Jesus said this to him.\par
    Since Judas was in charge of the money bag, some of the disciples thought that Jesus had told him to go and buy what they needed for the festival, or to give something to the poor.\par
    Judas accepted the bread and went out at once. It was night.\par
    After Judas had left, Jesus said, "Now the Son of Man's glory is revealed; now God's glory is revealed through him.\par
    And if God's glory is revealed through him, then God will reveal the glory of the Son of Man in himself, and he will do so at once.\par
    My children, I shall not be with you very much longer. You will look for me; but I tell you now what I told the Jewish authorities, "You cannot go where I am going.'\par
    And now I give you a new commandment: love one another. As I have loved you, so you must love one another.\par
    If you have love for one another, then everyone will know that you are my disciples."\par
    "Where are you going, Lord?" Simon Peter asked him. "You cannot follow me now where I am going," answered Jesus; "but later you will follow me."\par
    "Lord, why can't I follow you now?" asked Peter. "I am ready to die for you!"\par
    Jesus answered, "Are you really ready to die for me? I am telling you the truth: before the rooster crows you will say three times that you do not know me.\par
    "Do not be worried and upset," Jesus told them. "Believe in God and believe also in me.\par
    There are many rooms in my Father's house, and I am going to prepare a place for you. I would not tell you this if it were not so.\par
    And after I go and prepare a place for you, I will come back and take you to myself, so that you will be where I am.\par
    You know the way that leads to the place where I am going."\par
    Thomas said to him, "Lord, we do not know where you are going; so how can we know the way to get there?"\par
    Jesus answered him, "I am the way, the truth, and the life; no one goes to the Father except by me.\par
    Now that you have known me," he said to them, "you will know my Father also, and from now on you do know him and you have seen him."\par
    Philip said to him, "Lord, show us the Father; that is all we need."\par
    Jesus answered, "For a long time I have been with you all; yet you do not know me, Philip? Whoever has seen me has seen the Father. Why, then, do you say, "Show us the Father'?\par
    Do you not believe, Philip, that I am in the Father and the Father is in me? The words that I have spoken to you," Jesus said to his disciples, "do not come from me. The Father, who remains in me, does his own work.\par
    Believe me when I say that I am in the Father and the Father is in me. If not, believe because of the things I do.\par
    I am telling you the truth: those who believe in me will do what I do - yes, they will do even greater things, because I am going to the Father.\par
    And I will do whatever you ask for in my name, so that the Father's glory will be shown through the Son.\par
    If you ask me for anything in my name, I will do it.\par
    "If you love me, you will obey my commandments.\par
    I will ask the Father, and he will give you another Helper, who will stay with you forever.\par
    He is the Spirit, who reveals the truth about God. The world cannot receive him, because it cannot see him or know him. But you know him, because he remains with you and is in you.\par
    "When I go, you will not be left all alone; I will come back to you.\par
    In a little while the world will see me no more, but you will see me; and because I live, you also will live.\par
    When that day comes, you will know that I am in my Father and that you are in me, just as I am in you.\par
    "Those who accept my commandments and obey them are the ones who love me. My Father will love those who love me; I too will love them and reveal myself to them."\par
    Judas (not Judas Iscariot) said, "Lord, how can it be that you will reveal yourself to us and not to the world?"\par
    Jesus answered him, "Those who love me will obey my teaching. My Father will love them, and my Father and I will come to them and live with them.\par
    Those who do not love me do not obey my teaching. And the teaching you have heard is not mine, but comes from the Father, who sent me.\par
    "I have told you this while I am still with you.\par
    The Helper, the Holy Spirit, whom the Father will send in my name, will teach you everything and make you remember all that I have told you.\par
    "Peace is what I leave with you; it is my own peace that I give you. I do not give it as the world does. Do not be worried and upset; do not be afraid.\par
    You heard me say to you, "I am leaving, but I will come back to you.' If you loved me, you would be glad that I am going to the Father; for he is greater than I.\par
    I have told you this now before it all happens, so that when it does happen, you will believe.\par
    I cannot talk with you much longer, because the ruler of this world is coming. He has no power over me,\par
    but the world must know that I love the Father; that is why I do everything as he commands me. "Come, let us go from this place.\par
    "I am the real vine, and my Father is the gardener.\par
    He breaks off every branch in me that does not bear fruit, and he prunes every branch that does bear fruit, so that it will be clean and bear more fruit.\par
    You have been made clean already by the teaching I have given you.\par
    Remain united to me, and I will remain united to you. A branch cannot bear fruit by itself; it can do so only if it remains in the vine. In the same way you cannot bear fruit unless you remain in me.\par
    "I am the vine, and you are the branches. Those who remain in me, and I in them, will bear much fruit; for you can do nothing without me.\par
    Those who do not remain in me are thrown out like a branch and dry up; such branches are gathered up and thrown into the fire, where they are burned.\par
    If you remain in me and my words remain in you, then you will ask for anything you wish, and you shall have it.\par
    My Father's glory is shown by your bearing much fruit; and in this way you become my disciples.\par
    I love you just as the Father loves me; remain in my love.\par
    If you obey my commands, you will remain in my love, just as I have obeyed my Father's commands and remain in his love.\par
    "I have told you this so that my joy may be in you and that your joy may be complete.\par
    My commandment is this: love one another, just as I love you.\par
    The greatest love you can have for your friends is to give your life for them.\par
    And you are my friends if you do what I command you.\par
    I do not call you servants any longer, because servants do not know what their master is doing. Instead, I call you friends, because I have told you everything I heard from my Father.\par
    You did not choose me; I chose you and appointed you to go and bear much fruit, the kind of fruit that endures. And so the Father will give you whatever you ask of him in my name.\par
    This, then, is what I command you: love one another.\par
    "If the world hates you, just remember that it has hated me first.\par
    If you belonged to the world, then the world would love you as its own. But I chose you from this world, and you do not belong to it; that is why the world hates you.\par
    Remember what I told you: "Slaves are not greater than their master.' If people persecuted me, they will persecute you too; if they obeyed my teaching, they will obey yours too.\par
    But they will do all this to you because you are mine; for they do not know the one who sent me.\par
    They would not have been guilty of sin if I had not come and spoken to them; as it is, they no longer have any excuse for their sin.\par
    Whoever hates me hates my Father also.\par
    They would not have been guilty of sin if I had not done among them the things that no one else ever did; as it is, they have seen what I did, and they hate both me and my Father.\par
    This, however, was bound to happen so that what is written in their Law may come true: "They hated me for no reason at all.'\par
    "The Helper will come - the Spirit, who reveals the truth about God and who comes from the Father. I will send him to you from the Father, and he will speak about me.\par
    And you, too, will speak about me, because you have been with me from the very beginning.\par
    "I have told you this, so that you will not give up your faith.\par
    You will be expelled from the synagogues, and the time will come when those who kill you will think that by doing this they are serving God.\par
    People will do these things to you because they have not known either the Father or me.\par
    But I have told you this, so that when the time comes for them to do these things, you will remember what I told you. "I did not tell you these things at the beginning, for I was with you.\par
    But now I am going to him who sent me, yet none of you asks me where I am going.\par
    And now that I have told you, your hearts are full of sadness.\par
    But I am telling you the truth: it is better for you that I go away, because if I do not go, the Helper will not come to you. But if I do go away, then I will send him to you.\par
    And when he comes, he will prove to the people of the world that they are wrong about sin and about what is right and about God's judgment.\par
    They are wrong about sin, because they do not believe in me;\par
    they are wrong about what is right, because I am going to the Father and you will not see me any more;\par
    and they are wrong about judgment, because the ruler of this world has already been judged.\par
    "I have much more to tell you, but now it would be too much for you to bear.\par
    When, however, the Spirit comes, who reveals the truth about God, he will lead you into all the truth. He will not speak on his own authority, but he will speak of what he hears and will tell you of things to come.\par
    He will give me glory, because he will take what I say and tell it to you.\par
    All that my Father has is mine; that is why I said that the Spirit will take what I give him and tell it to you.\par
    "In a little while you will not see me any more, and then a little while later you will see me."\par
    Some of his disciples asked among themselves, "What does this mean? He tells us that in a little while we will not see him, and then a little while later we will see him; and he also says, "It is because I am going to the Father.'\par
    What does this "a little while' mean? We don't know what he is talking about!"\par
    Jesus knew that they wanted to question him, so he said to them, "I said, "In a little while you will not see me, and then a little while later you will see me.' Is this what you are asking about among yourselves?\par
    I am telling you the truth: you will cry and weep, but the world will be glad; you will be sad, but your sadness will turn into gladness.\par
    When a woman is about to give birth, she is sad because her hour of suffering has come; but when the baby is born, she forgets her suffering, because she is happy that a baby has been born into the world.\par
    That is how it is with you: now you are sad, but I will see you again, and your hearts will be filled with gladness, the kind of gladness that no one can take away from you.\par
    "When that day comes, you will not ask me for anything. I am telling you the truth: the Father will give you whatever you ask of him in my name.\par
    Until now you have not asked for anything in my name; ask and you will receive, so that your happiness may be complete.\par
    "I have used figures of speech to tell you these things. But the time will come when I will not use figures of speech, but will speak to you plainly about the Father.\par
    When that day comes, you will ask him in my name; and I do not say that I will ask him on your behalf,\par
    for the Father himself loves you. He loves you because you love me and have believed that I came from God.\par
    I did come from the Father, and I came into the world; and now I am leaving the world and going to the Father."\par
    Then his disciples said to him, "Now you are speaking plainly, without using figures of speech.\par
    We know now that you know everything; you do not need to have someone ask you questions. This makes us believe that you came from God."\par
    Jesus answered them, "Do you believe now?\par
    The time is coming, and is already here, when all of you will be scattered, each of you to your own home, and I will be left all alone. But I am not really alone, because the Father is with me.\par
    I have told you this so that you will have peace by being united to me. The world will make you suffer. But be brave! I have defeated the world!"\par
    After Jesus finished saying this, he looked up to heaven and said, "Father, the hour has come. Give glory to your Son, so that the Son may give glory to you.\par
    For you gave him authority over all people, so that he might give eternal life to all those you gave him.\par
    And eternal life means to know you, the only true God, and to know Jesus Christ, whom you sent.\par
    I have shown your glory on earth; I have finished the work you gave me to do.\par
    Father! Give me glory in your presence now, the same glory I had with you before the world was made.\par
    "I have made you known to those you gave me out of the world. They belonged to you, and you gave them to me. They have obeyed your word,\par
    and now they know that everything you gave me comes from you.\par
    I gave them the message that you gave me, and they received it; they know that it is true that I came from you, and they believe that you sent me.\par
    "I pray for them. I do not pray for the world but for those you gave me, for they belong to you.\par
    All I have is yours, and all you have is mine; and my glory is shown through them.\par
    And now I am coming to you; I am no longer in the world, but they are in the world. Holy Father! Keep them safe by the power of your name, the name you gave me, so that they may be one just as you and I are one.\par
    While I was with them, I kept them safe by the power of your name, the name you gave me. I protected them, and not one of them was lost, except the man who was bound to be lost - so that the scripture might come true.\par
    And now I am coming to you, and I say these things in the world so that they might have my joy in their hearts in all its fullness.\par
    I gave them your message, and the world hated them, because they do not belong to the world, just as I do not belong to the world.\par
    I do not ask you to take them out of the world, but I do ask you to keep them safe from the Evil One.\par
    Just as I do not belong to the world, they do not belong to the world.\par
    Dedicate them to yourself by means of the truth; your word is truth.\par
    I sent them into the world, just as you sent me into the world.\par
    And for their sake I dedicate myself to you, in order that they, too, may be truly dedicated to you.\par
    "I pray not only for them, but also for those who believe in me because of their message.\par
    I pray that they may all be one. Father! May they be in us, just as you are in me and I am in you. May they be one, so that the world will believe that you sent me.\par
    I gave them the same glory you gave me, so that they may be one, just as you and I are one:\par
    I in them and you in me, so that they may be completely one, in order that the world may know that you sent me and that you love them as you love me.\par
    "Father! You have given them to me, and I want them to be with me where I am, so that they may see my glory, the glory you gave me; for you loved me before the world was made.\par
    Righteous Father! The world does not know you, but I know you, and these know that you sent me.\par
    I made you known to them, and I will continue to do so, in order that the love you have for me may be in them, and so that I also may be in them."\par
    After Jesus had said this prayer, he left with his disciples and went across Kidron Brook. There was a garden in that place, and Jesus and his disciples went in.\par
    Judas, the traitor, knew where it was, because many times Jesus had met there with his disciples.\par
    So Judas went to the garden, taking with him a group of Roman soldiers, and some Temple guards sent by the chief priests and the Pharisees; they were armed and carried lanterns and torches.\par
    Jesus knew everything that was going to happen to him, so he stepped forward and asked them, "Who is it you are looking for?"\par
    "Jesus of Nazareth," they answered. "I am he," he said. Judas, the traitor, was standing there with them.\par
    When Jesus said to them, "I am he," they moved back and fell to the ground.\par
    Again Jesus asked them, "Who is it you are looking for?" "Jesus of Nazareth," they said.\par
    "I have already told you that I am he," Jesus said. "If, then, you are looking for me, let these others go.\par
    (He said this so that what he had said might come true: "Father, I have not lost even one of those you gave me.")\par
    Simon Peter, who had a sword, drew it and struck the High Priest's slave, cutting off his right ear. The name of the slave was Malchus.\par
    Jesus said to Peter, "Put your sword back in its place! Do you think that I will not drink the cup of suffering which my Father has given me?"\par
    Then the Roman soldiers with their commanding officer and the Jewish guards arrested Jesus, tied him up,\par
    and took him first to Annas. He was the father-in-law of Caiaphas, who was High Priest that year.\par
    It was Caiaphas who had advised the Jewish authorities that it was better that one man should die for all the people.\par
    Simon Peter and another disciple followed Jesus. That other disciple was well known to the High Priest, so he went with Jesus into the courtyard of the High Priest's house,\par
    while Peter stayed outside by the gate. Then the other disciple went back out, spoke to the girl at the gate, and brought Peter inside.\par
    The girl at the gate said to Peter, "Aren't you also one of the disciples of that man?" "No, I am not," answered Peter.\par
    It was cold, so the servants and guards had built a charcoal fire and were standing around it, warming themselves. So Peter went over and stood with them, warming himself.\par
    The High Priest questioned Jesus about his disciples and about his teaching.\par
    Jesus answered, "I have always spoken publicly to everyone; all my teaching was done in the synagogues and in the Temple, where all the people come together. I have never said anything in secret.\par
    Why, then, do you question me? Question the people who heard me. Ask them what I told them - they know what I said."\par
    When Jesus said this, one of the guards there slapped him and said, "How dare you talk like that to the High Priest!"\par
    Jesus answered him, "If I have said anything wrong, tell everyone here what it was. But if I am right in what I have said, why do you hit me?"\par
    Then Annas sent him, still tied up, to Caiaphas the High Priest.\par
    Peter was still standing there keeping himself warm. So the others said to him, "Aren't you also one of the disciples of that man?" But Peter denied it. "No, I am not," he said.\par
    One of the High Priest's slaves, a relative of the man whose ear Peter had cut off, spoke up. "Didn't I see you with him in the garden?" he asked.\par
    Again Peter said "No" - and at once a rooster crowed.\par
    Early in the morning Jesus was taken from Caiaphas' house to the governor's palace. The Jewish authorities did not go inside the palace, for they wanted to keep themselves ritually clean, in order to be able to eat the Passover meal.\par
    So Pilate went outside to them and asked, "What do you accuse this man of?"\par
    Their answer was, "We would not have brought him to you if he had not committed a crime."\par
    Pilate said to them, "Then you yourselves take him and try him according to your own law." They replied, "We are not allowed to put anyone to death.\par
    (This happened in order to make come true what Jesus had said when he indicated the kind of death he would die.)\par
    Pilate went back into the palace and called Jesus. "Are you the king of the Jews?" he asked him.\par
    Jesus answered, "Does this question come from you or have others told you about me?"\par
    Pilate replied, "Do you think I am a Jew? It was your own people and the chief priests who handed you over to me. What have you done?"\par
    Jesus said, "My kingdom does not belong to this world; if my kingdom belonged to this world, my followers would fight to keep me from being handed over to the Jewish authorities. No, my kingdom does not belong here!"\par
    So Pilate asked him, "Are you a king, then?" Jesus answered, "You say that I am a king. I was born and came into the world for this one purpose, to speak about the truth. Whoever belongs to the truth listens to me."\par
    "And what is truth?" Pilate asked. Then Pilate went back outside to the people and said to them, "I cannot find any reason to condemn him.\par
    But according to the custom you have, I always set free a prisoner for you during the Passover. Do you want me to set free for you the king of the Jews?"\par
    They answered him with a shout, "No, not him! We want Barabbas!" (Barabbas was a bandit.)\par
    Then Pilate took Jesus and had him whipped.\par
    The soldiers made a crown out of thorny branches and put it on his head; then they put a purple robe on him\par
    and came to him and said, "Long live the King of the Jews!" And they went up and slapped him.\par
    Pilate went back out once more and said to the crowd, "Look, I will bring him out here to you to let you see that I cannot find any reason to condemn him."\par
    So Jesus came out, wearing the crown of thorns and the purple robe. Pilate said to them, "Look! Here is the man!"\par
    When the chief priests and the Temple guards saw him, they shouted, "Crucify him! Crucify him!" Pilate said to them, "You take him, then, and crucify him. I find no reason to condemn him."\par
    The crowd answered back, "We have a law that says he ought to die, because he claimed to be the Son of God."\par
    When Pilate heard this, he was even more afraid.\par
    He went back into the palace and asked Jesus, "Where do you come from?" But Jesus did not answer.\par
    Pilate said to him, "You will not speak to me? Remember, I have the authority to set you free and also to have you crucified."\par
    Jesus answered, "You have authority over me only because it was given to you by God. So the man who handed me over to you is guilty of a worse sin."\par
    When Pilate heard this, he tried to find a way to set Jesus free. But the crowd shouted back, "If you set him free, that means that you are not the Emperor's friend! Anyone who claims to be a king is a rebel against the Emperor!"\par
    When Pilate heard these words, he took Jesus outside and sat down on the judge's seat in the place called "The Stone Pavement." (In Hebrew the name is "Gabbatha.")\par
    It was then almost noon of the day before the Passover. Pilate said to the people, "Here is your king!"\par
    They shouted back, "Kill him! Kill him! Crucify him!" Pilate asked them, "Do you want me to crucify your king?" The chief priests answered, "The only king we have is the Emperor!"\par
    Then Pilate handed Jesus over to them to be crucified. So they took charge of Jesus.\par
    He went out, carrying his cross, and came to "The Place of the Skull," as it is called. (In Hebrew it is called "Golgotha.")\par
    There they crucified him; and they also crucified two other men, one on each side, with Jesus between them.\par
    Pilate wrote a notice and had it put on the cross. "Jesus of Nazareth, the King of the Jews," is what he wrote.\par
    Many people read it, because the place where Jesus was crucified was not far from the city. The notice was written in Hebrew, Latin, and Greek.\par
    The chief priests said to Pilate, "Do not write "The King of the Jews,' but rather, "This man said, I am the King of the Jews.' "\par
    Pilate answered, "What I have written stays written."\par
    After the soldiers had crucified Jesus, they took his clothes and divided them into four parts, one part for each soldier. They also took the robe, which was made of one piece of woven cloth without any seams in it.\par
    The soldiers said to one another, "Let's not tear it; let's throw dice to see who will get it." This happened in order to make the scripture come true: "They divided my clothes among themselves and gambled for my robe." And this is what the soldiers did.\par
    Standing close to Jesus' cross were his mother, his mother's sister, Mary the wife of Clopas, and Mary Magdalene.\par
    Jesus saw his mother and the disciple he loved standing there; so he said to his mother, "He is your son."\par
    Then he said to the disciple, "She is your mother." From that time the disciple took her to live in his home.\par
    Jesus knew that by now everything had been completed; and in order to make the scripture come true, he said, "I am thirsty."\par
    A bowl was there, full of cheap wine; so a sponge was soaked in the wine, put on a stalk of hyssop, and lifted up to his lips.\par
    Jesus drank the wine and said, "It is finished!" Then he bowed his head and gave up his spirit.\par
    Then the Jewish authorities asked Pilate to allow them to break the legs of the men who had been crucified, and to take the bodies down from the crosses. They requested this because it was Friday, and they did not want the bodies to stay on the crosses on the Sabbath, since the coming Sabbath was especially holy.\par
    So the soldiers went and broke the legs of the first man and then of the other man who had been crucified with Jesus.\par
    But when they came to Jesus, they saw that he was already dead, so they did not break his legs.\par
    One of the soldiers, however, plunged his spear into Jesus' side, and at once blood and water poured out\par
    (The one who saw this happen has spoken of it, so that you also may believe. What he said is true, and he knows that he speaks the truth.)\par
    This was done to make the scripture come true: "Not one of his bones will be broken."\par
    And there is another scripture that says, "People will look at him whom they pierced."\par
    After this, Joseph, who was from the town of Arimathea, asked Pilate if he could take Jesus' body. (Joseph was a follower of Jesus, but in secret, because he was afraid of the Jewish authorities.) Pilate told him he could have the body, so Joseph went and took it away.\par
    Nicodemus, who at first had gone to see Jesus at night, went with Joseph, taking with him about one hundred pounds of spices, a mixture of myrrh and aloes.\par
    The two men took Jesus' body and wrapped it in linen cloths with the spices according to the Jewish custom of preparing a body for burial.\par
    There was a garden in the place where Jesus had been put to death, and in it there was a new tomb where no one had ever been buried.\par
    Since it was the day before the Sabbath and because the tomb was close by, they placed Jesus' body there.\par
    Early on Sunday morning, while it was still dark, Mary Magdalene went to the tomb and saw that the stone had been taken away from the entrance.\par
    She went running to Simon Peter and the other disciple, whom Jesus loved, and told them, "They have taken the Lord from the tomb, and we don't know where they have put him!"\par
    Then Peter and the other disciple went to the tomb.\par
    The two of them were running, but the other disciple ran faster than Peter and reached the tomb first.\par
    He bent over and saw the linen cloths, but he did not go in.\par
    Behind him came Simon Peter, and he went straight into the tomb. He saw the linen cloths lying there\par
    and the cloth which had been around Jesus' head. It was not lying with the linen cloths but was rolled up by itself.\par
    Then the other disciple, who had reached the tomb first, also went in; he saw and believed\par
    (They still did not understand the scripture which said that he must rise from death.)\par
    Then the disciples went back home.\par
    Mary stood crying outside the tomb. While she was still crying, she bent over and looked in the tomb\par
    and saw two angels there dressed in white, sitting where the body of Jesus had been, one at the head and the other at the feet.\par
    "Woman, why are you crying?" they asked her. She answered, "They have taken my Lord away, and I do not know where they have put him!"\par
    Then she turned around and saw Jesus standing there; but she did not know that it was Jesus.\par
    "Woman, why are you crying?" Jesus asked her. "Who is it that you are looking for?" She thought he was the gardener, so she said to him, "If you took him away, sir, tell me where you have put him, and I will go and get him."\par
    Jesus said to her, "Mary!" She turned toward him and said in Hebrew, "Rabboni!" (This means "Teacher.")\par
    "Do not hold on to me," Jesus told her, "because I have not yet gone back up to the Father. But go to my brothers and tell them that I am returning to him who is my Father and their Father, my God and their God."\par
    So Mary Magdalene went and told the disciples that she had seen the Lord and related to them what he had told her.\par
    It was late that Sunday evening, and the disciples were gathered together behind locked doors, because they were afraid of the Jewish authorities. Then Jesus came and stood among them. "Peace be with you," he said.\par
    After saying this, he showed them his hands and his side. The disciples were filled with joy at seeing the Lord.\par
    Jesus said to them again, "Peace be with you. As the Father sent me, so I send you."\par
    Then he breathed on them and said, "Receive the Holy Spirit.\par
    If you forgive people's sins, they are forgiven; if you do not forgive them, they are not forgiven."\par
    One of the twelve disciples, Thomas (called the Twin), was not with them when Jesus came.\par
    So the other disciples told him, "We have seen the Lord!" Thomas said to them, "Unless I see the scars of the nails in his hands and put my finger on those scars and my hand in his side, I will not believe."\par
    A week later the disciples were together again indoors, and Thomas was with them. The doors were locked, but Jesus came and stood among them and said, "Peace be with you."\par
    Then he said to Thomas, "Put your finger here, and look at my hands; then reach out your hand and put it in my side. Stop your doubting, and believe!"\par
    Thomas answered him, "My Lord and my God!"\par
    Jesus said to him, "Do you believe because you see me? How happy are those who believe without seeing me!"\par
    In his disciples' presence Jesus performed many other miracles which are not written down in this book.\par
    But these have been written in order that you may believe that Jesus is the Messiah, the Son of God, and that through your faith in him you may have life.\par
    After this, Jesus appeared once more to his disciples at Lake Tiberias. This is how it happened.\par
    Simon Peter, Thomas (called the Twin), Nathanael (the one from Cana in Galilee), the sons of Zebedee, and two other disciples of Jesus were all together.\par
    Simon Peter said to the others, "I am going fishing." "We will come with you," they told him. So they went out in a boat, but all that night they did not catch a thing.\par
    As the sun was rising, Jesus stood at the water's edge, but the disciples did not know that it was Jesus.\par
    Then he asked them, "Young men, haven't you caught anything?" "Not a thing," they answered.\par
    He said to them, "Throw your net out on the right side of the boat, and you will catch some." So they threw the net out and could not pull it back in, because they had caught so many fish.\par
    The disciple whom Jesus loved said to Peter, "It is the Lord!" When Peter heard that it was the Lord, he wrapped his outer garment around him (for he had taken his clothes off) and jumped into the water.\par
    The other disciples came to shore in the boat, pulling the net full of fish. They were not very far from land, about a hundred yards away.\par
    When they stepped ashore, they saw a charcoal fire there with fish on it and some bread.\par
    Then Jesus said to them, "Bring some of the fish you have just caught."\par
    Simon Peter went aboard and dragged the net ashore full of big fish, a hundred and fifty-three in all; even though there were so many, still the net did not tear.\par
    Jesus said to them, "Come and eat." None of the disciples dared ask him, "Who are you?" because they knew it was the Lord.\par
    So Jesus went over, took the bread, and gave it to them; he did the same with the fish.\par
    This, then, was the third time Jesus appeared to the disciples after he was raised from death.\par
    After they had eaten, Jesus said to Simon Peter, "Simon son of John, do you love me more than these others do?" "Yes, Lord," he answered, "you know that I love you." Jesus said to him, "Take care of my lambs."\par
    A second time Jesus said to him, "Simon son of John, do you love me?" "Yes, Lord," he answered, "you know that I love you." Jesus said to him, "Take care of my sheep."\par
    A third time Jesus said, "Simon son of John, do you love me?" Peter became sad because Jesus asked him the third time, "Do you love me?" and so he said to him, "Lord, you know everything; you know that I love you!" Jesus said to him, "Take care of my sheep.\par
    I am telling you the truth: when you were young, you used to get ready and go anywhere you wanted to; but when you are old, you will stretch out your hands and someone else will tie you up and take you where you don't want to go."\par
    (In saying this, Jesus was indicating the way in which Peter would die and bring glory to God.) Then Jesus said to him, "Follow me!"\par
    Peter turned around and saw behind him that other disciple, whom Jesus loved - the one who had leaned close to Jesus at the meal and had asked, "Lord, who is going to betray you?"\par
    When Peter saw him, he asked Jesus, "Lord, what about this man?"\par
    Jesus answered him, "If I want him to live until I come, what is that to you? Follow me!"\par
    So a report spread among the followers of Jesus that this disciple would not die. But Jesus did not say he would not die; he said, "If I want him to live until I come, what is that to you?"\par
    He is the disciple who spoke of these things, the one who also wrote them down; and we know that what he said is true.\par
    Now, there are many other things that Jesus did. If they were all written down one by one, I suppose that the whole world could not hold the books that would be written.\cf0\f2\fs22\par

